-- Acter, Lijun, RFM Corp., Samsung, Sino Union: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 2010-10-04T21:11:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-04/acter-lijun-rfm-corp-samsung-sino-union-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in  Asian trading , excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Philippine banks: The yield of the 91-day Philippine
treasury bill, which is used by banks to price loans, fell to
3.9 percent yesterday from 3.987 percent in the auction on Sept.
20.  Banco de Oro Unibank Inc.  (BDO PM), the nation’s biggest
bank by assets, gained 0.9 percent to 60.60 pesos.  Metropolitan
Bank & Trust Co.  (MBT PM), the second-largest lender by asset,
gained 3.3 percent to 73.60 pesos.  Acter Co. Ltd.  (5536 TT):  The company’s board of directors
approved a plan to offer 4.6 million new shares tentatively
priced at NT$70 each, Acter said in a statement to a local stock
exchange. The proceeds will be used to strengthen working
capital, the Taichung, central Taiwan-based maker of electric
and bio-medical facilities said. Acter was unchanged at NT$110.  Guangzhou R&F Properties Co.  (2777 HK): The property
developer said contracted sales jumped 65 percent in September
from a year earlier and 19 percent from August, according to an
e-mailed statement. Guangzhou slipped 0.4 percent to HK$10.86.  Hyundai Merchant Marine Co. (011200 KS): South Korea’s
second-largest shipping line plans to raise about 250 billion
won ($222 million) from a sale of bonds, according to two people
familiar with the matter. Hyundai Merchant advanced 4 percent to
48,700 won.  Lijun International Pharmaceutical (Holding) Co.  (2005 HK):
A shareholder in Lijun was offering 100 million shares for sale
at HK$2.81-HK$2.90 apiece, according to a term sheet obtained by
Bloomberg News. Lijun, a manufacturer of pharmaceutical products,
slid 0.7 percent to HK$3.02.  Malaysian Genomics Resource Centre Bhd.  (MGRC MK): Shares
of the Malaysian bioinformatics services provider will trade for
the first time on the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange. Malaysian
Genomics sold shares at 1.08 ringgit apiece in its initial
public offering.  PT Bank Negara Indonesia  (BBNI IJ): Indonesia’s third-
biggest state-owned bank will provide 600 billion rupiah ($67
million) in loans to the government to finance weapons and
equipment upgrades for the country’s army and police forces, the
lender said. Bank Negara climbed 0.7 percent to 3,700 rupiah.  RFM Corp.  (RFM PM): The Philippine food and drinks company
was rated “buy” with a 2.70 peso, 12-month share-price
estimate in initial coverage by ATR KimEng Securities Inc.
analyst  Laura Dy-Liacco . The stock rose 4.2 percent to 1.75
pesos.  Samsung Electronics Co.  (005930 KS): Asia’s biggest maker
of chips was rated “buy” in new coverage at Hana Daetoo by
equity analyst Ka-Keun Lee. Samsung climbed 0.4 percent to
780,000 won.  Sino Union Energy Investment Group Ltd.  (346 HK): The
investment company has started the second phase of exploratory
drilling in a block in southwest Madagascar, Le Midi reported,
citing Mining and Oil Minister  Mamy Ratovomalala . Sino Union
climbed 1.5 percent to 67 Hong Kong cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
